\"$\\\",\\\"$14\\\",null,{\\\"name\\\":\\\"Next.Metadata\\\",\\\"children\\\":\\\"$L1a\\\"}]}]}],[\\\"$\\\",\\\"meta\\\",null,{\\\"name\\\":\\\"next-size-adjust\\\",\\\"content\\\":\\\"\\\"}]]}]\\n10:[\\\"$\\\",\\\"link\\\",\\\"0\\\",{\\\"rel\\\":\\\"stylesheet\\\",\\\"href\\\":\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0npi_rp6qs2dq.css\\\",\\\"precedence\\\":\\\"next\\\",\\\"crossOrigin\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\",\\\"nonce\\\":\\\"$undefined\\\"}]\\n\"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,\"1b:I[85437,[\\\"/_next/static/chunks/04hm9vf8xmubm.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0y-.2i-zv25eo.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0~a.u3-2ydpng.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0d3shmwh5_nmn.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0lnjlo~xn6fto.js\\\"],\\\"Image\\\"]\\n1c:I[59095,[\\\"/_next/static/chunks/04hm9vf8xmubm.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0y-.2i-zv25eo.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0~a.u3-2ydpng.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0d3shmwh5_nmn.js\\\",\\\"/_next/static/chunks/0lnjlo~xn6fto.js\\\"],\\\"Reveal\\\"]\\n1d:T2ea0,\"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,\"\\u003ch1\\u003eCottontail Rabbit Hunting in Michigan's Thumb — Guided Hunts with Hotshot Outfitters\\u003c/h1\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eRabbit hunting is one of the great overlooked traditions in American hunting. Ask any hunter who grew up walking briar patches with a .22 or a shotgun, and they'll tell you it's where they learned to shoot — fast flushes, unpredictable direction changes, and cover so thick it'll rip your jacket before the rabbit even shows itself. Hotshot Outfitters guides cottontail rabbit hunts in Michigan's Thumb, and the habitat around Port Hope and Huron County is genuinely some of the best small game country in the state.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eIf you're looking for guided cottontail rabbit hunting in Michigan — whether you're a seasoned small game hunter or introducing someone to the sport — this page covers everything you need to know.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eWhy Cottontail Rabbit Hunting in Michigan's Thumb Is Underrated\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eMost hunters driving through Huron County see the agricultural fields and think deer. Fair enough. But the brushy fencerows, overgrown ditches, multiflora rose thickets, and weedy field edges that border all those cornfields and soybean fields? That's prime cottontail habitat, and it holds rabbits in numbers that would surprise most hunters who've never worked it.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eCottontail rabbits thrive in exactly the kind of edge cover that dominates this region: brushy tangles near open feeding areas, dense grass and shrub patches along drainage ditches, and the scrubby second-growth that fills in along fence lines and woodlot edges. This is hunter-on-foot country. You push through cover, the rabbit bolts, and you've got about two seconds to make your shot before it disappears into the next thicket. It's fast, physical, and addictive.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eMichigan hunting doesn't get more accessible than this. You don't need a treestand or a months-long scouting mission. You need good boots, a shotgun or .22, and the willingness to push cover until the rabbits start moving.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eMichigan Cottontail Rabbit Season\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eMichigan DNR establishes the cottontail rabbit season annually. As a general planning reference:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eSeason\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Typically opens September 15 and runs through March 31\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eDaily Bag Limit\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Check current MI DNR regulations — limits apply\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003ePossession Limit\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Twice the daily bag limit in most cases\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eThe September through October window gives you warm-weather hunting in dense green cover — tough going, but rabbits are concentrated in predictable areas near food. November and December hunting after a frost or early snowfall is often the most productive: cover thins out, rabbit tracks are visible in snow, and the animals become more predictable in their movements. February and March offer late-season hunting when rabbits are on late-winter food sources and pressure has dropped off.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eAlways verify the current season dates and bag limits at the \\u003ca href=\\\"https://www.michigan.gov/dnr\\\"\\u003eMI DNR website\\u003c/a\\u003e before your trip. Regulations can shift between years.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eWhat to Expect on a Guided Cottontail Hunt\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eHotshot Outfitters' guided rabbit hunts are active hunts. You will be on your feet, pushing cover, walking fencerows, and working through the kind of thick brush that rabbits use as their first line of defense. This is not a sit-and-wait hunt.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eThe Hunt\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Your guide knows where rabbits concentrate on the properties we access — the best thickets, the warmest south-facing slopes where rabbits sun themselves on cold mornings, the drainage ditches that hold cover year-round. Rather than wandering and hoping, you're walking targeted cover with a guide who has 20+ years of local knowledge telling you where to focus.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eDogs\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Beagle dogs can be incorporated into rabbit hunts. A good beagle changes the dynamic entirely — the dog finds the rabbit, pushes it in a circle back toward the hunters, and the shooting opportunities multiply dramatically. If you want to hunt with dogs, ask about availability when you book.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eShooting\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Most cottontail hunting is shotgun work — 20-gauge or 12-gauge with #6 or #7.5 shot is the standard setup. A .22 rimfire works in situations where rabbits are sitting tight and you have time for a precision shot. Expect shots in the 10–30 yard range in thick cover, often through brush. Lead your shots.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eTerrain: What the Hunting Ground Looks Like\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eHuron County's rabbit hunting terrain is a mix of agricultural edge cover and woodlot periphery. The specific types of cover we work include:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eFencerow tangles\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Old hedgerows and fence lines that have grown up into dense multiflora rose, Russian olive, and native shrubs. Rabbits use these as travel corridors and bedding areas throughout the season.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eDrainage ditches\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Overgrown ditches along field edges hold cattail stands, tall grass, and brushy cover that rabbits use for security. Working these linear features produces consistent flushes.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eWoodlot edges\\u003c/strong\\u003e: The transition from open field to timber often includes a brushy fringe of regenerating shrubs and saplings. This is classic cottontail bedding habitat, especially on south-facing edges that capture winter sun.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eOvergrown fields\\u003c/strong\\u003e: Older fields returning to brush, with tall grass and scattered shrub cover, are rabbit magnets. This type of early successional habitat is exactly what cottontails prefer.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eLicensing and What You Need\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eEvery hunter on a guided rabbit hunt in Michigan must hold:\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eValid Michigan Hunting License\\u003c/strong\\u003e (base license, which covers small game including rabbits)\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eNon-residents must purchase a non-resident license\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eMichigan's small game license is straightforward and relatively affordable. Purchase it online through the MI DNR portal or at any authorized license agent in the state. Rabbits do not require a separate stamp or tag beyond the base small game license.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eConfirm current licensing requirements with the MI DNR before your trip. We will answer licensing questions during the booking process, but the responsibility for legal licensing rests with each hunter.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eWhat We Supply vs. What You Bring\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eHotshot Outfitters provides:\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eAccess to private hunting ground with established rabbit habitat\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eGuide with 20+ years of Huron County experience\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eKnowledge of productive cover locations and rabbit concentrations\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eOptional hunting dog support (confirm availability at booking)\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eYou bring:\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cul\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eValid Michigan hunting license\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eYour preferred firearm — 20 or 12-gauge shotgun, or .22 rimfire\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eAppropriate ammunition (#6 or #7.5 for shotgun; .22 LR for rimfire)\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eBriar-proof or brush-proof pants and jacket (not optional — this cover is brutal)\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eBoots with ankle support — you will be walking uneven terrain for hours\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eBlaze orange (required during firearm deer season if rabbit and deer seasons overlap — check DNR rules for concurrent seasons)\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003cli\\u003eLayers appropriate for the season\\u003c/li\\u003e\\n\\u003c/ul\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eGear Notes for Michigan Rabbit Hunting\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eRabbit hunting is gear-simple but clothing-demanding. The cover you'll be pushing through will destroy ordinary pants in a single morning. Invest in briar-proof or upland hunting pants — Filson, Carhartt, or any purpose-built upland brush pant will save your legs. Same goes for your jacket if you're pushing dense rose thickets.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eFootwear matters. You'll be walking for hours on uneven agricultural ground, through wet drainage ditches and across plowed field edges. Waterproof boots with ankle support keep you comfortable and mobile. Rubber boots work well for wet early-season hunting; insulated leather hunting boots work better for cold late-season conditions.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eFor shotgunners, open chokes perform best in close-cover situations. Improved cylinder or modified choke gives you the spread you need at typical rabbit-hunting distances. If you're shooting tight cover where shots are measured in yards, improved cylinder is the right call.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eWhy Rabbit Hunting Is Worth Your Time\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eCottontail rabbit hunting is the perfect introduction to wingshooting and upland hunting. The shots are fast and challenging, the season is long, and the hunting ground is accessible without the logistical complexity of a big game hunt. For hunters who want to sharpen their shotgun skills, there is no better practice than a morning in a briar patch full of cottontails.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eIt's also genuinely fun in a way that's hard to replicate with other species. You're moving, working as a team, covering ground, and the action comes in bursts that keep you alert. Rabbit hunting with a beagle is one of the classic American hunting experiences, and we're proud to offer it in the kind of country that does it justice.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eFrequently Asked Questions\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: Is cottontail rabbit hunting good for beginners or kids?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eIt's one of the best hunts for new hunters. Action is frequent, the equipment requirements are simple, and the physical demands are manageable for most fitness levels. It's also a relatively affordable guided experience. If you're introducing someone to hunting, a rabbit hunt is an excellent choice.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: What shotgun loads work best for cottontail rabbits?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eFor 12-gauge, #6 or #7.5 lead shot in a 2.75\\\" or 3\\\" shell is the standard. For 20-gauge, same shot sizes work well. Open chokes — improved cylinder or modified — are preferred for the close-range shots you'll typically take in heavy cover. Steel shot is not required for cottontails.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: Can I bring my own beagle?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003ePossibly. We accommodate hunters who want to run their own dogs on a case-by-case basis depending on property considerations and group dynamics. Discuss this during the booking process and we'll tell you what's feasible.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: Is blaze orange required for rabbit hunting in Michigan?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eDuring concurrent firearm deer season (November 15–30 and potentially other firearm seasons), Michigan law requires hunters in the field to wear blaze orange. Check current MI DNR regulations for the specific season you're hunting. We will keep you informed of requirements applicable to your hunt date.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: How physically demanding is a guided rabbit hunt?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eYou should expect to walk several miles over the course of a half-day or full-day hunt, through varied and sometimes rough terrain. The cover can be dense and physically challenging to push through. Most reasonably fit hunters handle it without issue, but if you have mobility concerns, discuss them with us at booking and we'll plan accordingly.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003eQ: Do you offer half-day rabbit hunting options?\\u003c/strong\\u003e\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eYes. Rabbit hunts can be structured as half-day or full-day experiences. Contact us to discuss the format that fits your schedule and group.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003chr\\u003e\\n\\u003ch2\\u003eBook Your Michigan Rabbit Hunt\\u003c/h2\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eCottontail rabbit hunting in Michigan's Thumb is one of the most entertaining and overlooked hunting experiences in the Midwest. Hotshot Outfitters puts you on productive ground with 20+ years of local knowledge behind the operation. Whether you're after a classic rabbit hunt with dogs or a fast-paced solo push through cover, we can make it happen.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eContact us to check availability and get on the schedule.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003e\\u003cstrong\\u003ePhone:\\u003c/strong\\u003e (989) 551-4551 or (989) 670-4336\\n\\u003cstrong\\u003eAddress:\\u003c/strong\\u003e 6900 Huron City Road, Port Hope, MI 48468\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\\u003cp\\u003eCall us. Rabbit season is long — let's make the most of it.\\u003c/p\\u003e\\n\"])</script><script>self.__next_f.push([1,\"12:[[\\\"$\\\",\\\"script\\\",null,{\\\"type\\\":\\\"application/ld+json\\\",\\\"dangerouslySetInnerHTML\\\":{\\\"__html\\\":\\\"{\\\\\\\"@context\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"https://schema.org\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"@type\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Article\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"headline\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Cottontail Rabbit Hunting in Michigan | Guided Hunts with Hotshot Outfitters\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"description\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\